<subsection><title>Check Your Understanding</title>
<p><ol>
<li><p>Name three algebraic methods for solving a quadratic equation.</p></li>
<li><p>Give an example of a quadratic trinomial that is the square of a binomial.</p></li>
<li><p>In Activity 3, what were the two parts named for solving an equation by completing the square?</p></li>
<li><p>What is wrong with the following solution?
        <md><mrow>2x^2-8x+3 \amp = 0</mrow>
            <mrow>2x^2-8x+16 \amp = -3 + 16</mrow>
            <mrow>(2x-4)^2 \amp = 13</mrow>
            <mrow>x \amp = \dfrac{4 \pm \sqrt{13}}{2}</mrow></md></p></li>
</ol></p></subsection>

<subsection><title>Wrap Up</title>
<p>In this Lesson, we worked on the following skills and goals related to quadratic models:</p>
<p><ul>
  <li><p>Add a constant to <m>x^2+bx</m> to create a perfect square</p></li>
  <li><p>Solve quadratic equations by completing the square</p></li>
</ul></p>

<commentary audience="instructor"><title>Questions for Writing or Discussion</title>
<p><ol>
<li><p>Explain how to tell whether <m>x^2+bx+c</m> is the square of a binomial.</p></li>
<li><p>Discuss the difference between an exact solution and a decimal approximation.</p></li>
<li><p>How can you decide which of the three methods for solving a quadratic equation you should use?</p></li>
<li><p>How does creating the square of a binomial help us solve a quadratic equation?</p></li>
</ol></p></commentary>
</subsection>

